      "text": "The spectroscopic analysis for the sample with UUID `a9ffa147-5667-4a17-be84-6a05079a9aff` leads to the following conclusion:\n\n**1. Molecular Formula and Unsaturation:**\nThe obtained molecular formula is **C11H23NO2**, and the molecular weight is approximately 201.17 Da. The calculated Degree of Unsaturation (DBE) is **1**. This suggests the presence of one double bond (likely a carbonyl) or one ring.\n\n**2. Functional Group Analysis (IR):**\nThe IR spectrum shows a peak at **3348 cm⁻¹**, indicative of an N-H stretch. A strong carbonyl absorption is observed at **1690 cm⁻¹**, which, combined with the Amide II band at **1520 cm⁻¹**, suggests a carbamate (urethane) or amide functionality. The C-H stretching region (2956–2871 cm⁻¹) indicates an aliphatic nature.\n\n**3. NMR Analysis and Structure Determination:**\n*   **1H NMR:**\n    *   A prominent singlet at **δ 1.42 (9H)** strongly indicates a **tert-butyl group**, likely part of a Boc (tert-butoxycarbonyl) protecting group.\n    *   A broad singlet at **δ 4.54 (1H)** corresponds to the N-H proton.\n    *   The remaining protons integrate to 13H, consistent with a **C6H13** alkyl chain attached to the nitrogen.\n    *   A doublet at **δ 0.85 (6H, J=6.7 Hz)** indicates a terminal **isopropyl group** `(-CH(CH3)2)`.\n    *   A multiplet at **δ 3.07 (2H)** corresponds to the methylene group adjacent to the nitrogen (`-NH-CH2-`).\n    *   Other multiplets at δ 1.52 (1H, methine) and δ 1.10–1.48 (4H, methylenes) complete the **4-methylpentyl** chain structure (`-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH(CH3)2`).\n*   **13C NMR:**\n    *   The carbonyl peak at **δ 155.92** and the quaternary carbon at **δ 78.91** confirm the **Boc group** (`O-C(=O)-NH-`).\n    *   The intense peak at **δ 28.38** corresponds to the three methyl carbons of the tert-butyl group.\n    *   The remaining peaks (δ 40.83, 27.89, 27.72, 25.91, 22.50) account for the 6 carbons of the 4-methylpentyl chain, with δ 22.50 representing the two equivalent methyls of the isopropyl tail and δ 40.83 the N-adjacent methylene.\n\n**4. Conclusion:**\nThe data is fully consistent with **tert-butyl (4-methylpentyl)carbamate** (also known as N-Boc-4-methylpentylamine or N-Boc-isohexylamine). The presence of the Boc group and the specific isohexyl chain (inferred from the terminal isopropyl doublet and chain length) leaves no other reasonable isomers.\n\nFINAL_RESULT:\n  UUID: a9ffa147-5667-4a17-be84-6a05079a9aff\n  PREDICTED_SMILES: CC(C)CCCNC(=O)OC(C)(C)C\n  CONFIDENCE: 0.98\n  REASON_BRIEF: The structure is confirmed as tert-butyl (4-methylpentyl)carbamate. 1H and 13C NMR clearly show a Boc group (s, 9H; 155.9 ppm) and a 4-methylpentyl chain (terminal isopropyl doublet at 0.85 ppm, N-CH2 at 3.07 ppm). Formula and DBE match perfectly.",
